TUSDATA.geofeatures=[
{id:"appalachians",name:"Appalachian Mountains",kind:"mountains",lon:-79.5,lat:38.6,angle:-38,tier:1,
 facts:[["Highest point","Mount Mitchell, 6,684 ft"],["Age","Ancient orogenies, roughly 480-300 million years ago"],["Extent","Roughly 1,500 miles, Alabama to Newfoundland"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1800,text:"Raised by continental collisions 480-300 million years ago and worn to rounded ridges, the mountains were homeland to Cherokee, Haudenosaunee, Shawnee, and Lenape peoples. Britain's Proclamation Line of 1763 tried to hold settlement east of the crest, but Daniel Boone's road through the Cumberland Gap in 1775 funneled settlers into Kentucky."},
  {from:1800,to:1900,text:"Turnpikes, canals, and railroads pierced the ridges. The 1838 Trail of Tears forced most Cherokee from the southern mountains. Salt, iron, and then coal and timber industries expanded after the Civil War, and industrial logging began stripping old-growth hardwood coves while subsistence farm communities filled the hollows."},
  {from:1900,to:1970,text:"Coal mining dominated the central ranges, with company towns and labor conflicts such as Blair Mountain in 1921. The introduced chestnut blight killed billions of American chestnuts by the 1940s. New Deal-era work created Shenandoah and Great Smoky Mountains national parks and the Blue Ridge Parkway, and the Appalachian Trail was completed in 1937."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"Surface mining, including mountaintop removal, reshaped parts of West Virginia and Kentucky as underground coal employment fell. Forests regrew across much of the chain, now recognized as a global center of salamander and freshwater diversity. Acid rain damage eased after Clean Air Act amendments, and outdoor recreation became an economic mainstay."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","National Park Service"]},
{id:"rockies",name:"Rocky Mountains",kind:"mountains",lon:-107.3,lat:43.5,angle:-20,tier:1,
 facts:[["Highest point","Mount Elbert, 14,433 ft"],["Formed","Laramide orogeny, about 80-55 million years ago"],["Extent","About 3,000 miles, British Columbia to New Mexico"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1820,text:"Pushed up mainly during the Laramide orogeny about 80-55 million years ago, the Rockies form the continental spine and the headwaters of the Missouri, Colorado, Rio Grande, and Snake. Ute, Shoshone, Blackfeet, Crow, and Salish peoples hunted and wintered in the high parks, and horses spread through the region during the 1700s."},
  {from:1820,to:1870,text:"Beaver trappers worked the streams in the 1820s and 1830s, meeting at annual rendezvous, until fashion shifts and depletion ended the trade. Emigrant wagon trails crossed at South Pass from the 1840s, and the 1859 Pikes Peak gold rush drew roughly 100,000 people toward the Colorado ranges."},
  {from:1870,to:1940,text:"Railroads crossed the passes, and silver and gold camps like Leadville and Butte boomed. Yellowstone became the first national park in 1872, followed by Glacier in 1910 and Rocky Mountain in 1915. Ute, Shoshone, and other nations were confined to reservations as mining, logging, and ranching claimed the valleys."},
  {from:1940,to:2026,text:"Postwar ski resorts, interstate highways, and mountain towns transformed local economies, and transbasin tunnels now carry water beneath the divide to growing cities. Warming has shrunk glaciers and snowpack, while bark beetle epidemics and larger wildfires have killed broad swaths of forest; wolves and grizzlies recovered in the northern ranges."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","National Park Service"]},
{id:"sierranevada",name:"Sierra Nevada",kind:"mountains",lon:-119.3,lat:37.7,angle:-35,tier:1,
 facts:[["Highest point","Mount Whitney, about 14,500 ft; tallest in the contiguous US"],["Length","About 400 miles"],["Rock","Granite batholith emplaced roughly 100 million years ago"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1848,text:"A tilted block of Mesozoic granite lifted along faults on its steep eastern face, the Sierra was crossed by trading trails linking Paiute, Washoe, Mono, and Miwok peoples, who exchanged obsidian, salt, acorns, and pine nuts over its passes. Spanish colonists named the snowy range from afar but rarely entered; the Donner Party's 1846-47 ordeal showed its winter dangers."},
  {from:1848,to:1900,text:"Gold found at Coloma in 1848 set off the rush that remade California and devastated Native communities. Hydraulic mining blasted foothill gravels until courts curbed the debris in 1884. Loggers cut giant sequoia and sugar pine, while Yosemite gained protection by federal grant in 1864 and as a national park in 1890; John Muir founded the Sierra Club in 1892."},
  {from:1900,to:1970,text:"The range became California's water tower: San Francisco dammed Hetch Hetchy in 1923, Los Angeles tapped streams east of the crest, and federal and state dams stored snowmelt for Central Valley farms. Kings Canyon National Park followed in 1940, and ski areas and Lake Tahoe resorts expanded rapidly after World War II."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"Decades of fire suppression left dense forests primed for drought; the 2012-2016 drought killed well over 100 million trees, and megafires in 2020-2021 burned into giant sequoia groves, killing thousands of ancient trees. Managers now reintroduce prescribed fire, while a shrinking snowpack complicates water supply for most Californians."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","National Park Service"]},
{id:"cascades",name:"Cascade Range",kind:"mountains",lon:-121.7,lat:45.8,angle:-85,tier:2,
 facts:[["Highest point","Mount Rainier, 14,410 ft"],["Character","Volcanic arc above the Cascadia subduction zone"],["Length","About 700 miles, northern California to British Columbia"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1840,text:"The Cascades are young stratovolcanoes built above the Cascadia subduction zone atop older volcanic highlands. Yakama, Klickitat, Molala, Cowlitz, and Chinookan peoples harvested huckleberries in subalpine meadows and salmon in the rivers cutting the range; oral traditions such as the Bridge of the Gods record landslides and eruptions along the Columbia."},
  {from:1840,to:1900,text:"Oregon Trail emigrants rafted the Columbia Gorge or took the Barlow Road around Mount Hood after 1846. Treaties in 1855 confined tribes to reservations while reserving gathering and fishing rights in the mountains. Railroads tunneled the passes in the 1880s, and commercial logging pushed up the wet western slopes."},
  {from:1900,to:1970,text:"Mount Rainier became a national park in 1899, and national forests soon covered most of the range. Fire lookouts, Civilian Conservation Corps trails, and postwar logging roads spread as old-growth cutting peaked. Dams on the Columbia and Cascade tributaries brought power but blocked salmon; North Cascades National Park followed in 1968."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"Mount St. Helens erupted on May 18, 1980, killing 57 people and flattening some 230 square miles of forest, a natural laboratory ever since. Spotted owl litigation sharply curtailed old-growth logging around 1990. USGS observatories now monitor the volcanoes while the range's glaciers, among the largest in the contiguous US, retreat rapidly."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","National Park Service"]},
{id:"alaskarange",name:"Alaska Range & Denali",kind:"mountains",lon:-151.0,lat:63.0,angle:-8,tier:2,
 facts:[["Highest point","Denali, 20,310 ft; highest in North America"],["Length","About 400 miles along the Denali Fault"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1867,text:"An arc of peaks raised along the Denali Fault where the Pacific plate drives beneath Alaska, the range carries North America's highest summit, Denali, the tall one in Koyukon Athabascan. Dena'ina and Koyukon peoples hunted caribou, moose, and Dall sheep on its flanks; Russian traders on the coast rarely reached the interior."},
  {from:1867,to:1917,text:"After the 1867 US purchase of Alaska, prospectors spread inland; gold strikes in the Kantishna Hills in 1905 brought a brief rush to the range's north side. In 1913 Hudson Stuck's expedition made the first ascent of Denali, with Alaska Native climber Walter Harper the first person to stand on the summit."},
  {from:1917,to:1980,text:"Mount McKinley National Park was created in 1917, largely to protect Dall sheep and caribou from market hunting; the Alaska Railroad reached the area in the 1920s and a single park road followed. In 1980 the Alaska lands act tripled the protected area and renamed it Denali National Park and Preserve."},
  {from:1980,to:2026,text:"More than a thousand mountaineers now attempt Denali most years from the Kahiltna Glacier. A 2015 survey fixed the summit at 20,310 feet, and the federal name became Denali that year; a 2025 order restored Mount McKinley in federal usage while Alaska retains Denali. The range's glaciers are thinning and permafrost is degrading."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","National Park Service"]},
{id:"adirondacks",name:"Adirondack Mountains",kind:"mountains",lon:-74.2,lat:44.1,angle:0,tier:3,
 facts:[["Highest point","Mount Marcy, 5,344 ft"],["Bedrock","About 1.1 billion years old"],["Adirondack Park","About 6 million acres"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1850,text:"A dome of billion-year-old basement rock uplifted in geologically recent time and still rising slowly, the Adirondacks hold dozens of peaks above 4,000 feet. Mohawk and Abenaki peoples hunted and fished the region between their settled valleys. Colonial wars swirled around lakes George and Champlain, but the interior stayed little mapped into the 1830s."},
  {from:1850,to:1900,text:"Iron mines, hemlock-bark tanneries, and log drives down the Hudson's headwaters industrialized the woods. Fear that deforestation would silt the Erie Canal and city water supplies led New York to create the Forest Preserve in 1885 and the Adirondack Park in 1892, made forever wild by the state constitution in 1894."},
  {from:1900,to:1970,text:"Great camps, railroads, and Saranac Lake's tuberculosis sanatoria drew visitors, and Lake Placid hosted the 1932 Winter Olympics. Logging continued on private tracts inside the park's patchwork of public and private land, while state wilderness slowly recovered from nineteenth-century fires and heavy cutting."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"The Adirondack Park Agency, created in 1971, brought land-use planning across the six-million-acre park, the largest in the contiguous US. Acid rain from distant smokestacks sterilized hundreds of lakes before the 1990 Clean Air Act amendments; waters and loons have substantially recovered, and Lake Placid hosted the Olympics again in 1980."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","Encyclopaedia Britannica"]},
{id:"ozarks",name:"Ozark Plateau",kind:"plateau",lon:-92.6,lat:36.8,angle:0,tier:3,
 facts:[["Area","About 47,000 square miles"],["Highest ridges","About 2,560 ft, in the Boston Mountains"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1830,text:"An uplifted, deeply dissected plateau of Paleozoic dolomite and limestone over a Precambrian volcanic core, the Ozarks are laced with caves and some of the largest springs on the continent. The Osage dominated the region, hunting across it from prairie towns, with Caddoan peoples on the southern fringes; French colonists mined lead near Ste. Genevieve in the 1700s."},
  {from:1830,to:1900,text:"The Osage ceded the plateau by 1825 and were removed to Kansas, then Oklahoma; Trail of Tears routes crossed the hills in 1838-39. Scots-Irish subsistence farmers settled the hollows. After the Civil War, railroads brought industrial logging that leveled the shortleaf pine forests."},
  {from:1900,to:1970,text:"Lead and zinc mining boomed in the Tri-State district around Joplin and in Missouri's Old Lead Belt. Federal dams, including Bull Shoals and Table Rock in the 1950s, impounded the White River for power and flood control and created a lake tourism economy; Ozark National Scenic Riverways protected the Current and Jacks Fork in 1964."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"The Buffalo became the first national river in 1972, ending dam plans there. Second-growth oak and pine now cover most of the plateau, and float fishing and Branson tourism anchor the economy. Karst geology leaves groundwater unusually vulnerable to pollution, while springs such as Big Spring still discharge hundreds of millions of gallons daily."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","National Park Service"]},
{id:"blackhills",name:"Black Hills",kind:"mountains",lon:-103.6,lat:44.1,angle:0,tier:3,
 facts:[["Highest point","Black Elk Peak, 7,242 ft; highest US summit east of the Rockies"],["Core rocks","About 1.8 billion years old, domed up roughly 60 million years ago"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1868,text:"An oval dome where ancient rocks rose through the plains cover, the forested Black Hills, Paha Sapa, are sacred to the Lakota, who took the region in the 1700s, and figure in Cheyenne, Arapaho, and Kiowa traditions as well. The 1868 Fort Laramie Treaty reserved the hills to the Great Sioux Reservation, closed to settlement."},
  {from:1868,to:1900,text:"Custer's 1874 expedition announced gold on French Creek, and miners flooded in illegally; Deadwood boomed in 1876. After the Great Sioux War, Congress seized the hills in 1877 without Lakota consent. The Homestake Mine at Lead began a 125-year run as one of the hemisphere's most productive gold mines."},
  {from:1900,to:1980,text:"Wind Cave became a national park in 1903, and Custer State Park rebuilt a bison herd from a remnant. Gutzon Borglum carved Mount Rushmore between 1927 and 1941, and the Crazy Horse Memorial began in 1948. Tourism joined mining and timber as the regional economic base."},
  {from:1980,to:2026,text:"In 1980 the Supreme Court held the 1877 seizure an unconstitutional taking and awarded about $105 million; the Lakota refused the money, insisting on return of land, and the unclaimed fund has grown to well over a billion dollars. Homestake closed in 2002 and now houses an underground physics laboratory; Black Elk Peak was renamed in 2016."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","National Park Service"]},
{id:"greatplains",name:"Great Plains",kind:"plains",lon:-101.0,lat:41.0,angle:-90,tier:1,
 facts:[["Area","Roughly 500,000 square miles"],["Elevation","Rises from about 1,000 ft in the east to over 6,000 ft at the Rockies"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1830,text:"Built from sediment washed east off the Rockies over millions of years, the plains carried tens of millions of bison on the continent's greatest grassland. Horses spreading north through the 1700s remade the Comanche, Lakota, Cheyenne, Kiowa, and Blackfeet into mounted bison-hunting powers that dominated the region for a century."},
  {from:1830,to:1890,text:"Overland trails and then railroads cut the bison range in two. Hide hunters killed millions of animals in the 1870s and early 1880s, leaving only a few hundred wild bison by the mid-1880s and breaking the economic base of Plains nations as the US confined them to reservations. The 1862 Homestead Act and barbed wire brought farm settlement."},
  {from:1890,to:1950,text:"Plow-up of the shortgrass in wet years met catastrophe in the 1930s Dust Bowl, when drought and bare fields loosed black blizzards over the southern plains and hundreds of thousands of people left the land. Soil conservation districts, shelterbelt planting, and grassland restoration followed under the New Deal."},
  {from:1950,to:2026,text:"Center-pivot irrigation from the Ogallala Aquifer greened the High Plains after 1950, but withdrawals far outpace recharge and parts of Texas and Kansas have lost much of their usable groundwater. Rural counties depopulate while wind farms spread; bison, back to roughly half a million mostly in managed herds, anchor grassland restoration efforts."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","Encyclopaedia Britannica"]},
{id:"greatbasin",name:"Great Basin",kind:"basin",lon:-116.8,lat:39.9,angle:0,tier:2,
 facts:[["Area","About 190,000 square miles of internal drainage; no outlet to the sea"],["High point","Wheeler Peak, 13,063 ft"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1840,text:"Stretched by crustal extension into more than a hundred parallel ranges and valleys, the Great Basin drains entirely inward; no stream reaches the ocean. Western Shoshone, Northern Paiute, Goshute, and Washoe peoples followed seasonal rounds of pinyon nuts, seeds, fish, and waterfowl. Fur brigades crossed in the 1820s and 1830s, trapping streams bare."},
  {from:1840,to:1900,text:"California-bound emigrants followed the Humboldt River corridor from the 1840s. The 1859 Comstock Lode made Virginia City a silver metropolis and stripped hillsides of pinyon and Tahoe timber for mine works and fuel. The 1863 Treaty of Ruby Valley recognized Western Shoshone lands even as the 1869 transcontinental railroad crossed them."},
  {from:1900,to:1970,text:"Mining cycles, open-range ranching, and railroad towns defined a sparse economy. From 1951 the Nevada Test Site detonated hundreds of nuclear devices, about a hundred of them above ground, on lands the Western Shoshone still claim under treaty; downwind communities bore the fallout. Growing cities began reaching for the basin's scarce water."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"Gold mining along Nevada's Carlin Trend made the state one of the world's leading producers. Great Basin National Park, created in 1986, protects Wheeler Peak and ancient bristlecone pines, among the oldest living trees on Earth. Terminal lakes such as Pyramid and Walker became battlegrounds over upstream diversion, with tribal litigation restoring some flows."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","National Park Service"]},
{id:"mojave",name:"Mojave Desert",kind:"desert",lon:-116.2,lat:35.1,angle:0,tier:3,
 facts:[["Area","About 25,000 square miles"],["Signature plant","Joshua tree (Yucca brevifolia)"],["Contains","Death Valley, the lowest ground in North America"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1850,text:"A high rain-shadow desert between the Sierra Nevada and the Colorado River, marked by Joshua trees and creosote basins. Mojave farmers lived along the river while Chemehuevi, Serrano, and Kawaiisu peoples used its springs and trade paths; the Mojave Road linked river to coast, and the Old Spanish Trail crossed the desert after 1829."},
  {from:1850,to:1920,text:"The US Army posted Fort Mojave on the river in 1859 and fought the river peoples. Railroads crossed the desert in the 1880s, spawning water-stop towns like Barstow and Needles, while borax, silver, and gold camps flickered through the ranges; twenty-mule teams hauled borax until rails arrived."},
  {from:1920,to:1994,text:"Route 66 carried Dust Bowl migrants and postwar tourists across the desert. World War II brought Patton's Desert Training Center and enduring military installations, including Edwards Air Force Base, where the sound barrier fell in 1947, China Lake, and Fort Irwin. Los Angeles suburbs pushed into the western desert."},
  {from:1994,to:2026,text:"The 1994 California Desert Protection Act created Mojave National Preserve and enlarged Joshua Tree and Death Valley parks. Utility-scale solar fields now compete with desert tortoise habitat, and the 2020 Dome Fire killed over a million Joshua trees, a species increasingly stressed by heat, drought, and fire cycles fed by invasive grasses."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","National Park Service"]},
{id:"sonoran",name:"Sonoran Desert",kind:"desert",lon:-112.3,lat:32.6,angle:0,tier:3,
 facts:[["Area","Roughly 100,000 square miles in the US and Mexico"],["Saguaro","Can exceed 40 ft and live 150-200 years"],["Rainfall","Two rainy seasons: winter storms and summer monsoon"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1854,text:"The most biologically diverse North American desert, with two rainy seasons feeding saguaro and organ pipe cactus forests. Hohokam ancestors of the O'odham had dug hundreds of miles of canals along the Salt and Gila centuries earlier; Tohono O'odham, Akimel O'odham, Quechan, and Cocopah peoples farmed and gathered as Spanish missions spread after the 1690s."},
  {from:1854,to:1911,text:"The 1854 Gadsden Purchase put the desert's northern half in the United States, and the Southern Pacific Railroad reached Tucson in 1880. Upstream settler diversion of the Gila River in the 1870s-90s devastated Akimel O'odham farms, pushing a grain-exporting people toward famine."},
  {from:1911,to:1980,text:"Roosevelt Dam, completed in 1911, launched the Salt River Project, and irrigated cotton, citrus, and cattle spread across the valleys; Phoenix boomed after 1945 with air conditioning. Saguaro and Organ Pipe Cactus national monuments protected cactus forest in the 1930s, while heavy groundwater pumping cracked and subsided valley floors, prompting Arizona's 1980 groundwater code."},
  {from:1980,to:2026,text:"The Central Arizona Project canal began delivering Colorado River water to Phoenix and Tucson in the 1980s and 1990s, and the Gila River Indian Community won one of the nation's largest water settlements in 2004. Border barrier construction cut wildlife corridors through protected desert, while record heat tests saguaros and the fast-growing cities."}
 ],
 sources:["National Park Service","U.S. Geological Survey"]},
{id:"coloradoplateau",name:"Colorado Plateau",kind:"plateau",lon:-110.3,lat:36.9,angle:0,tier:3,
 facts:[["Area","About 130,000 square miles"],["Average elevation","Roughly 5,000 ft"],["Rock record","Spans nearly 2 billion years"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1850,text:"A mile-high stack of flat-lying sandstone, shale, and limestone carved into canyons and mesas. Hopi, Zuni, and other Pueblo descendants of Ancestral Puebloan builders, along with Dine, Ute, and Southern Paiute peoples, farmed, herded, and traded across it. Spain's Dominguez-Escalante expedition circled the plateau in 1776 without finding a route to California."},
  {from:1850,to:1920,text:"Mormon colonists settled river valleys from the 1850s to 1870s; the Navajo endured the Long Walk to Bosque Redondo in 1864 before returning by treaty in 1868 to a reservation that grew into the nation's largest. John Wesley Powell's 1869 and 1871-72 river surveys mapped the canyon country, and railroads brought early tourism."},
  {from:1920,to:1980,text:"Route 66, the national parks, and Fred Harvey tourism sold plateau scenery, while the 1950s uranium boom left Navajo miners with lasting radiation illness and hundreds of abandoned mines. Glen Canyon Dam flooded a canyon of the Colorado in 1963, and coal strip mines and power plants fed distant cities."},
  {from:1980,to:2026,text:"The Grand Circle parks now draw millions of visitors, straining gateway towns. Bears Ears National Monument, proclaimed in 2016, shrunk in 2017, and restored in 2021, brought formal tribal co-management to ancestral lands. Drought since 2000 has pulled Lake Powell to record lows, re-exposing Glen Canyon, while dark skies and slickrock recreation drive the economy."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","National Park Service"]},
{id:"centralvalley",name:"Central Valley",kind:"valley",lon:-120.5,lat:37.2,angle:-35,tier:3,
 facts:[["Length","About 450 miles"],["Area","Roughly 20,000 square miles"],["Subsidence","Land near Mendota has sunk nearly 30 ft from groundwater pumping"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1848,text:"An alluvial trough between the Sierra and the Coast Ranges, once a mosaic of tule marsh, grassland, and riparian forest around Tulare Lake, then the largest freshwater lake west of the Mississippi. Yokuts, Miwok, Nisenan, and Wintun peoples lived densely on salmon, waterfowl, and acorns; Spanish soldiers raided the valley but never colonized it."},
  {from:1848,to:1900,text:"The gold rush built river ports at Sacramento and Stockton, while disease, militia violence, and dispossession devastated valley tribes. Hydraulic mining debris buried farmland until an 1884 injunction; bonanza wheat farms and then irrigation colonies spread across the valley floor as reclamation districts drained the tule basins."},
  {from:1900,to:1970,text:"Irrigation triumphed: Tulare Lake vanished into cotton fields, and the federal Central Valley Project from the 1930s and State Water Project from the 1960s moved Sierra snowmelt through dams and canals. The valley became the nation's richest farm region, worked by successive immigrant labor forces, while groundwater pumping sank land near Mendota nearly 30 feet."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"The valley grows about a quarter of America's table food. Salmon runs collapsed behind dams, and a 2009 settlement restarted flows in the dried San Joaquin. The 2014 groundwater law began regulating pumping after wells went dry in drought, and Tulare Lake briefly reappeared in the floods of 2023."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","Encyclopaedia Britannica"]},
{id:"grandcanyon",name:"Grand Canyon",kind:"canyon",lon:-112.6,lat:36.2,angle:0,tier:2,
 facts:[["Length","277 river miles"],["Depth","About one mile"],["Oldest rocks","Vishnu basement, about 1.8 billion years old"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1869,text:"The Colorado River has cut through the uplifted plateau for five to six million years, exposing rocks down to 1.8-billion-year-old basement: a gorge a mile deep, up to 18 miles wide, and 277 river miles long. Havasupai and Hualapai people lived within and along it; Hopi, Zuni, Dine, and Southern Paiute peoples hold it sacred."},
  {from:1869,to:1919,text:"John Wesley Powell's 1869 expedition ran the canyon's rapids and fixed its name. Prospectors found tourism paid better than ore, and the Santa Fe Railway reached the South Rim in 1901. Theodore Roosevelt, urging Americans to leave it as it is, made it a game preserve and then a national monument in 1908; Congress created the park in 1919."},
  {from:1919,to:1975,text:"Rim villages, trails, and Civilian Conservation Corps work served soaring visitation. Havasupai and Hualapai lands were squeezed by the park until Congress returned 185,000 acres to the Havasupai in 1975. Glen Canyon Dam, closed upstream in 1963, replaced warm muddy floods with cold clear releases, eroding beaches and imperiling native fish."},
  {from:1975,to:2026,text:"Experimental high-flow dam releases since 1996 attempt to rebuild sandbars, and the humpback chub has partially recovered. Nearly five million visitors a year crowd the rims. Uranium mining near the canyon was curbed by a 2012 mineral withdrawal and by the 2023 Baaj Nwaavjo I'tah Kukveni national monument, proclaimed with tribal backing."}
 ],
 sources:["National Park Service","U.S. Geological Survey"]},
{id:"deathvalley",name:"Death Valley",kind:"desert",lon:-116.9,lat:36.4,angle:0,tier:3,
 facts:[["Lowest point","Badwater Basin, 282 ft below sea level"],["Heat record","134 F at Furnace Creek in 1913, hottest air temperature reliably recorded on Earth"],["Park area","About 3.4 million acres"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1849,text:"A fault-bounded basin still dropping between the Panamint and Amargosa ranges, Death Valley holds North America's lowest ground at Badwater, 282 feet below sea level. The Timbisha Shoshone lived at its springs and mesquite groves for the past thousand years, moving to cooler uplands each summer. Lost forty-niners crossing in 1849 gave the valley its name."},
  {from:1849,to:1933,text:"Borax gathered from the salt flats made the valley famous after 1881: from 1883 to 1888 twenty-mule teams hauled loads 165 miles to the railhead at Mojave. Gold-era camps such as Rhyolite and Skidoo boomed and died in the 1900s, and Death Valley Scotty's tall tales drew the first tourists."},
  {from:1933,to:1994,text:"A 1933 national monument brought Civilian Conservation Corps roads and winter tourism to Furnace Creek, while the Timbisha were confined to a small village without recognized land. The 134-degree reading of July 1913 stands as the highest air temperature reliably recorded on Earth, and mining continued in the monument for decades."},
  {from:1994,to:2026,text:"The 1994 Desert Protection Act made Death Valley the largest national park in the contiguous US at 3.4 million acres. The Timbisha Homeland Act of 2000 restored 7,500 acres, the first reservation created inside a national park. Recent summers have neared 130 degrees, and floods in 2022-23 briefly returned a lake to the valley floor."}
 ],
 sources:["National Park Service","U.S. Geological Survey"]},
{id:"mississippi",name:"Mississippi River",kind:"river",lon:-91.1,lat:33.6,angle:0,tier:1,
 facts:[["Length","About 2,340 miles"],["Basin","About 1.2 million square miles; roughly 40% of the contiguous US"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1811,text:"Draining some 40 percent of the contiguous US, the river built its floodplain and delta from continental sediment. Mound-building civilizations, including Cahokia, had flourished on it centuries earlier; Ojibwe, Dakota, Quapaw, Natchez, Chickasaw, and Choctaw peoples held its reaches. Misi-ziibi, the Ojibwe great river, passed among France, Spain, and Britain until the 1803 Louisiana Purchase."},
  {from:1811,to:1900,text:"The steamboat New Orleans descended the river in 1811, opening two-way commerce; cotton and sugar economies built on slavery lined the lower valley, and removal-era steamboats carried southeastern nations west. Levee building accelerated decade by decade, and Eads' jetties opened a reliable deep channel at the mouth in 1879."},
  {from:1900,to:1945,text:"The levees-only policy failed catastrophically in the 1927 flood, which inundated about 27,000 square miles and displaced roughly 700,000 people, falling hardest on Black sharecroppers. The 1928 Flood Control Act gave the Army Corps of Engineers spillways such as Bonnet Carre and Morganza, and 1930s locks and dams turned the upper river into a barge staircase."},
  {from:1945,to:2026,text:"Diesel towboats now push enormous grain and petrochemical tonnage, and the Old River Control Structure has held the river out of the Atchafalaya's steeper path since 1963. Farm nutrients feed a Gulf hypoxic dead zone averaging several thousand square miles each summer, while record floods in 1993, 2011, and 2019 tested the engineered system."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Army Corps of Engineers","U.S. Geological Survey"]},
{id:"missouri",name:"Missouri River",kind:"river",lon:-100.3,lat:46.0,angle:0,tier:1,
 facts:[["Length","About 2,340 miles; longest river in the US"],["Basin","Roughly 530,000 square miles"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1830,text:"The longest river in the United States, the silt-heavy Big Muddy drains the northern plains from the Rockies. Mandan, Hidatsa, and Arikara earthlodge towns made its middle reaches a continental trade hub, with Lakota, Blackfeet, and Crow ranging beyond. Lewis and Clark ascended it in 1804-05, following a French fur trade already generations old."},
  {from:1830,to:1890,text:"Fur posts such as Fort Union gathered bison robes, and steamboats fought snags and shifting bars to reach Fort Benton by 1860. The 1837 smallpox epidemic devastated the river villages, killing most of the Mandan. Railroads then ended the steamboat era, and the river nations were confined to reservations along their old river."},
  {from:1890,to:1970,text:"The 1944 Pick-Sloan Plan built six mainstem dams, Fort Peck first, then Garrison, Oahe, and others, creating the nation's largest reservoir system. The pools drowned hundreds of thousands of acres of wooded bottomland on Fort Berthold, Standing Rock, Cheyenne River, and other reservations, while the lower river was channelized into a narrow barge chute."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"Engineering eliminated most sandbars and side channels; the pallid sturgeon, least tern, and piping plover became federally protected, and habitat programs attempt repair. The 2011 flood strained every mainstem dam, and the 2016-17 Standing Rock protests against the Dakota Access Pipeline crossing at Lake Oahe drew worldwide attention to the river."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Army Corps of Engineers","U.S. Geological Survey"]},
{id:"ohio",name:"Ohio River",kind:"river",lon:-86.3,lat:37.9,angle:0,tier:2,
 facts:[["Length","981 miles"],["Flow","Largest tributary of the Mississippi by volume"],["Basin","About 200,000 square miles"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1800,text:"Formed where the Allegheny and Monongahela meet at Pittsburgh, the Ohio, from the Seneca Ohi:yo, was the contested gateway west: rivalry over its forks ignited the French and Indian War in 1754. Shawnee, Miami, Lenape, and Wyandot towns defended the valley until Fallen Timbers in 1794 and the Treaty of Greenville."},
  {from:1800,to:1900,text:"Flatboats and, after 1811, steamboats carried the settler flood downriver. The Ohio became the legal line between slavery and free soil, crossed by thousands of freedom seekers on the Underground Railroad. Coal, iron, and glass industrialized its banks, and Louisville's 1830 canal finally bypassed the Falls of the Ohio."},
  {from:1900,to:1970,text:"Movable wicket dams canalized the full river by 1929 for barge traffic. The January 1937 flood, the valley's worst, put Louisville and Cincinnati underwater and killed hundreds, spurring reservoir construction. By mid-century the river ran as an industrial sewer, and the 1948 ORSANCO compact began interstate cleanup."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"Modern high-lift dams replaced the wickets, keeping the Ohio among the busiest freight waterways in the country. Clean Water Act-era work restored sport fisheries and riverfront cities, though harmful algal blooms in 2015 and 2019 and periodic chemical spills on tributaries showed that the watershed's industrial legacy endures."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Army Corps of Engineers","Encyclopaedia Britannica"]},
{id:"columbia",name:"Columbia River",kind:"river",lon:-119.9,lat:45.9,angle:0,tier:2,
 facts:[["Length","About 1,240 miles"],["Basin","Roughly 260,000 square miles"],["Flow","Largest river by volume entering the Pacific from North America"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1811,text:"The great river of the West cut its gorge through the Cascades across stacked lava flows, and Ice Age Missoula floods scoured its scablands. At Celilo Falls and The Dalles, Chinookan and Sahaptin-speaking peoples ran one of the continent's oldest fisheries and trade fairs on enormous salmon runs. Robert Gray crossed the bar in 1792; Lewis and Clark descended in 1805."},
  {from:1811,to:1900,text:"Astoria, founded in 1811, anchored the fur trade, and the Hudson's Bay Company ruled from Fort Vancouver until Oregon Trail settlement tipped the region American. Treaties in 1855 reserved tribal fishing at usual and accustomed places. Salmon canneries multiplied after 1866, taking millions of fish with wheels, traps, and gillnets."},
  {from:1900,to:1957,text:"Federal dams remade the river: Bonneville in 1938 with fish ladders, Grand Coulee in 1942 without, walling salmon out of the upper basin. Cheap power smelted aluminum and ran the wartime Hanford plutonium works, which contaminated the reach beside it. In 1957 The Dalles Dam drowned Celilo Falls, the oldest continuously used fishery in North America."},
  {from:1957,to:2026,text:"More than a dozen mainstem dams now regulate the river under a 1964 treaty with Canada, renegotiated in the 2020s. Salmon runs fell to a fraction of historic size, with thirteen stocks federally listed; tribal fisheries co-management, hatchery reform, spill programs, and Hanford cleanup define the modern river, along with debate over breaching the lower Snake dams."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","NOAA","U.S. Army Corps of Engineers"]},
{id:"colorado",name:"Colorado River",kind:"river",lon:-113.9,lat:34.9,angle:0,tier:2,
 facts:[["Length","About 1,450 miles"],["Basin","About 246,000 square miles in seven states and Mexico"],["Serves","Roughly 40 million people"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1869,text:"Rising in the Rockies and carving the Grand Canyon on its run toward the Gulf of California, the Colorado watered Ute, Dine, Hopi, Mojave, Chemehuevi, Quechan, and Cocopah homelands; lower-river peoples farmed its spring floods. John Wesley Powell's 1869 voyage first documented its canyons end to end."},
  {from:1869,to:1935,text:"Steamboats worked the lower river to Yuma, and an irrigation canal breach flooded the Salton Sink in 1905-07, creating the Salton Sea. The 1922 Colorado River Compact divided the river among seven states using unusually wet-year flow estimates, promising more water than the river reliably carries, and left tribes out; Hoover Dam was completed in 1935, creating Lake Mead."},
  {from:1935,to:2000,text:"The plumbing spread: the All-American Canal, Glen Canyon Dam and Lake Powell in 1963, and the Central Arizona Project by 1993, with a 1944 treaty allotting Mexico a share. Since the 1960s the river has only rarely reached the sea, and its once-vast delta wetlands in Mexico withered to a remnant."},
  {from:2000,to:2026,text:"A megadrought beginning in 2000, the region's driest stretch in over a millennium, cut flows roughly 20 percent; lakes Mead and Powell hit record lows in 2022, forcing shortage declarations and emergency conservation deals among the 40 million people served. A 2014 experimental pulse flow briefly reunited river and sea, and post-2026 operating rules remain under negotiation."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","Encyclopaedia Britannica"]},
{id:"riogrande",name:"Rio Grande",kind:"river",lon:-104.9,lat:30.4,angle:0,tier:2,
 facts:[["Length","About 1,900 miles"],["Border","Forms roughly 1,250 miles of the US-Mexico boundary"],["Headwaters","About 12,000 ft in Colorado's San Juan Mountains"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1848,text:"Flowing from Colorado's San Juan Mountains through the Rio Grande Rift toward the Gulf, the river sustained Pueblo farming towns for many centuries, alongside Apache and, later, Comanche power. Spanish colonists arrived in 1598, taking Pueblo water and labor; the 1680 Pueblo Revolt expelled them for a dozen years. Acequia irrigation ditches shaped valley life."},
  {from:1848,to:1916,text:"The 1848 Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo made the river an international border for more than 1,200 miles. Steamboats briefly worked the lower reaches, while upstream diversions in Colorado's San Luis Valley dried New Mexico farms by the 1880s, prompting Mexican protests and a 1906 convention delivering water at El Paso."},
  {from:1916,to:1970,text:"Elephant Butte Dam, completed in 1916, regulated the upper river for irrigation; the 1938 compact split flows among Colorado, New Mexico, and Texas, and a 1944 treaty divided lower-river waters with Mexico around the international Falcon and Amistad dams. Below El Paso, a so-called Forgotten River reach began running dry most years."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"Overallocation, invasive salt cedar, and deepening drought leave long stretches dry, and the endangered Rio Grande silvery minnow survives mainly in a mid-New Mexico remnant. In 2001 the river failed to reach the Gulf, its mouth closed by a sandbar. Water-delivery debts strain US-Mexico relations, and border barriers added new controversy in the 2020s."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","Encyclopaedia Britannica"]},
{id:"snake",name:"Snake River",kind:"river",lon:-114.4,lat:43.0,angle:0,tier:3,
 facts:[["Length","About 1,080 miles"],["Hells Canyon","Nearly 7,900 ft deep; deepest river gorge in North America"],["Shoshone Falls","212 ft, higher than Niagara"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1810,text:"The Columbia's largest tributary arcs from Yellowstone country across southern Idaho's volcanic plain, over Shoshone Falls, and through Hells Canyon, the deepest river gorge in North America. Shoshone and Bannock bands fished salmon below the falls, and the Nez Perce wintered in the canyon; Lewis and Clark reached its lower waters in 1805."},
  {from:1810,to:1900,text:"Fur brigades of the 1810s-30s deliberately trapped the beaver streams bare to discourage rivals. Oregon Trail wagons followed the river's rim from the 1840s, crossing at Three Island Ford. Gold rushes brought miners; the Nez Perce were driven from the canyon country in the 1877 war, and Shoshone-Bannock peoples were confined at Fort Hall."},
  {from:1900,to:1975,text:"Reclamation-era dams, beginning with Milner in 1905, diverted virtually the whole river into Magic Valley canals, building Idaho's irrigated potato and sugar-beet belt above the Eastern Snake Plain Aquifer. The Hells Canyon dam complex of 1958-67 blocked salmon from the upper basin, and four federal lower-river dams built by 1975 gave Lewiston barge access to the sea."},
  {from:1975,to:2026,text:"Snake River salmon and steelhead were federally listed in the 1990s; a single sockeye, Lonesome Larry, returned to Redfish Lake in 1992. Whether to breach the four lower Snake dams became the Northwest's defining river debate, addressed in federal-tribal agreements in 2023, while managed recharge works to stabilize the declining aquifer."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","NOAA"]},
{id:"tennessee",name:"Tennessee River",kind:"river",lon:-87.6,lat:34.9,angle:0,tier:3,
 facts:[["Length","652 miles"],["Dams","Nine mainstem dams operated by the Tennessee Valley Authority"],["Basin","About 41,000 square miles"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1838,text:"Formed near Knoxville and looping 652 miles through the Southeast, the river takes its name from the Cherokee town Tanasi. Cherokee, Muscogee, Chickasaw, and Yuchi peoples lived along it atop older Mississippian mound centers. Settler flatboats braved the Muscle Shoals rapids; Chickamauga Cherokee resistance contested the valley into the 1790s, and removal followed in 1838."},
  {from:1838,to:1933,text:"Steamboats worked the navigable reaches, but Muscle Shoals blocked through commerce despite canal attempts. The Civil War made the river an invasion corridor past forts Henry and Donelson, Shiloh, and Chattanooga. Wilson Dam, begun for World War I nitrate production, was completed in 1925 and ignited the national public-power debate."},
  {from:1933,to:1980,text:"The Tennessee Valley Authority, created in 1933, built a staircase of nine mainstem dams, electrified farms, controlled floods and malaria, and displaced thousands of families for reservoirs like Norris. TVA power ran the Oak Ridge uranium plants in World War II, and the snail darter fight over Tellico Dam reached the Supreme Court in 1978."},
  {from:1980,to:2026,text:"The dammed river settled into life as a barge highway and a chain of recreation lakes. TVA shifted from coal toward nuclear and gas amid air-quality battles and the 2008 Kingston coal-ash spill, one of the nation's largest industrial waste releases. The snail darter, transplanted and recovered, came off the endangered list in 2022."}
 ],
 sources:["Encyclopaedia Britannica","U.S. Geological Survey"]},
{id:"hudson",name:"Hudson River",kind:"river",lon:-73.8,lat:42.4,angle:0,tier:3,
 facts:[["Length","315 miles"],["Tidal estuary","153 miles, from New York Harbor to Troy"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1807,text:"A fjord-like tidal estuary for 153 miles up to Troy, called Muhheakantuck, the river that flows both ways, by the Mahican; Mahican and Lenape homelands became Dutch and then English trade corridors after 1609. In the Revolution both sides fought for the river, and the great chain at West Point barred British ships after 1778."},
  {from:1807,to:1900,text:"Fulton's 1807 steamboat proved the river a highway, and the 1825 Erie Canal joined it to the Great Lakes, making New York the continent's premier port. Sloops and barges carried bricks, ice, and stone; the Hudson River School painters made its scenery America's first artistic icon while factories and tanneries fouled tributaries."},
  {from:1900,to:1970,text:"Railroads and highways walled the banks, and cement plants and power stations rose. General Electric plants discharged PCBs into the upper river from 1947 to 1977, and raw sewage closed beaches. The 1962 proposal for a pumped-storage plant at Storm King Mountain ignited a landmark legal fight that helped create modern environmental law."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"Clean Water Act enforcement and citizen activism, from the sloop Clearwater to the first riverkeeper organization, revived the estuary: eagles, herring, and sturgeon returned, and Manhattan's shoreline became parkland. GE dredged PCB-contaminated sediment from 2009 to 2015, though fish consumption advisories persist along the recovering river."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","Encyclopaedia Britannica"]},
{id:"yukon",name:"Yukon River",kind:"river",lon:-157.0,lat:63.2,angle:0,tier:3,
 facts:[["Length","About 1,980 miles; roughly 1,280 in Alaska"],["Basin","About 330,000 square miles"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1867,text:"Rising in Canada and crossing the full width of Alaska to the Bering Sea, the Yukon runs nearly 2,000 miles, silt-gray and braided. Gwich'in and Koyukon Athabascan peoples upriver and Yup'ik people at the delta built lifeways on king and chum salmon, moose, and caribou; Russian and Hudson's Bay traders planted a few posts in the 1830s-40s."},
  {from:1867,to:1900,text:"After the Alaska purchase, American traders and missionaries moved upriver, and epidemics followed the trade routes. The 1896 Klondike strike on a Canadian tributary sent tens of thousands over the passes in 1897-98; sternwheelers crowded the river, and woodcutting camps stripped long stretches of bank to fuel their boilers."},
  {from:1900,to:1970,text:"Fairbanks gold shifted the rush in the early 1900s, and dredges chewed tributary valleys for decades. Sternwheelers gave way to airplanes; villages consolidated around missions and schools, while fish camps, sled dogs, and the annual freeze-up and breakup still set the rhythm of river life."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"The 1971 Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act and 1980 lands act reshaped ownership and subsistence rights, and the pipeline haul road bridged the river in 1975, still its only Alaska road crossing. Chinook and chum runs crashed in the 2010s-20s, closing fisheries basin-wide; a 2024 US-Canada agreement suspended Chinook harvests for seven years."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","National Park Service"]},
{id:"lakesuperior",name:"Lake Superior",kind:"lake",lon:-87.6,lat:47.6,angle:0,tier:2,
 facts:[["Area","31,700 square miles; largest freshwater lake on Earth by surface area"],["Maximum depth","1,332 ft"],["Volume","Holds roughly 10% of Earth's surface fresh water"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1840,text:"The largest freshwater lake on Earth by area fills a basin opened by the billion-year-old Midcontinent Rift and deepened by glaciers. Gichi-gami to the Ojibwe, it anchors Anishinaabe migration history at Madeline Island, and its native copper was worked for thousands of years. Voyageur canoes tied the lake into the fur trade through Grand Portage."},
  {from:1840,to:1900,text:"Treaties of 1842 and 1854 ceded shorelines while reserving Ojibwe fishing and gathering rights. Keweenaw copper made Michigan the nation's leading producer, and after the Soo Locks opened in 1855, iron from the Marquette, Gogebic, and Mesabi ranges flowed east in ore boats, the raw stream of the American steel age."},
  {from:1900,to:1975,text:"Ore ports, commercial fishing, and lumbering peaked. Sea lamprey invading through shipping canals collapsed lake trout by the 1950s, and herring and whitefish fisheries shrank. Taconite tailings were dumped at Silver Bay until courts intervened in the 1970s, and the freighter Edmund Fitzgerald went down with 29 men in a November 1975 gale."},
  {from:1975,to:2026,text:"Lamprey control and stocking restored self-sustaining lake trout by the 1990s, a rare Great Lakes recovery. The coldest and cleanest Great Lake is also among the fastest-warming large lakes on Earth, with shrinking winter ice; Isle Royale's wolf and moose study, running since 1958, continues after wolves were reintroduced."}
 ],
 sources:["NOAA","U.S. Geological Survey"]},
{id:"lakemichigan",name:"Lake Michigan",kind:"lake",lon:-87.1,lat:43.7,angle:0,tier:2,
 facts:[["Area","22,300 square miles"],["Maximum depth","925 ft"],["Status","Only Great Lake entirely within the US"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1830,text:"Gouged by ice sheets along an ancient bedrock lowland, Lake Michigan is edged by the world's largest freshwater dune systems. Ojibwe, Odawa, and Potawatomi of the Three Fires Confederacy, with Menominee, Ho-Chunk, and Miami peoples, fished whitefish and grew corn along its shores; French traders worked the Green Bay and Chicago portages."},
  {from:1830,to:1900,text:"The 1833 Treaty of Chicago forced most Potawatomi west of the Mississippi. Lumber schooners carried Michigan and Wisconsin pine to build Chicago, which grew from portage town to rail metropolis; the Chicago and Peshtigo fires struck the same night in 1871. Overfishing began cutting into whitefish and sturgeon stocks."},
  {from:1900,to:1970,text:"In 1900 Chicago reversed its river into the Mississippi basin to protect its water intake, linking the two watersheds. Steel and refining industrialized the southern shore, and the Indiana Dunes were split between port and park in 1966 compromises. Lamprey and alewife invasions wrecked native fisheries; Pacific salmon stocking began in 1966."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"Sleeping Bear Dunes became a national lakeshore in 1970 and Indiana Dunes a national park in 2019. Quagga and zebra mussels filtered the food web thin, clearing the water while starving prey fish, and electric barriers on the Chicago canal now guard against invasive carp. Chicago's diversion remains capped by Supreme Court decree."}
 ],
 sources:["NOAA","U.S. Geological Survey"]},
{id:"lakehuron",name:"Lake Huron",kind:"lake",lon:-82.4,lat:44.8,angle:0,tier:2,
 facts:[["Area","About 23,000 square miles including Georgian Bay"],["Maximum depth","750 ft"],["Manitoulin","Largest freshwater island on Earth"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1830,text:"Second largest of the Great Lakes by area, with tens of thousands of islands including Manitoulin, the largest freshwater island on Earth. French explorers reached it first among the lakes and called it the freshwater sea; its name recalls the Wendat. Anishinaabe peoples held its shores, netting whitefish and trout at Mackinac and Saginaw."},
  {from:1830,to:1900,text:"Treaties in 1836 and 1855 ceded most of the Michigan shoreline while reserving fishing rights still exercised and litigated today. Saginaw Valley pine made Michigan the world's lumber capital in the 1870s-80s, and cutover slash fed the deadly Thumb fires of 1871 and 1881. Commercial fishing towns dotted the coast."},
  {from:1900,to:1970,text:"The Great Storm of November 1913 sank eight ships on Huron with all hands, the worst disaster in Great Lakes history. Limestone from Rogers City, the world's largest such quarry, fed steelmaking. Sea lamprey arriving by the 1940s destroyed lake trout, and the deepwater commercial fishery collapsed by mid-century."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"Invasive quagga mussels collapsed the alewife base around 2003, ending a stocked Chinook salmon boom but favoring recovering native lake trout and walleye. Saginaw Bay's contaminated sediments and algal problems eased under cleanup programs, and the Thunder Bay marine sanctuary now protects nearly a hundred shipwrecks in its clear water."}
 ],
 sources:["NOAA","Encyclopaedia Britannica"]},
{id:"lakeerie",name:"Lake Erie",kind:"lake",lon:-81.2,lat:42.2,angle:0,tier:2,
 facts:[["Area","9,910 square miles"],["Average depth","62 ft; shallowest Great Lake"],["Retention time","About 2.6 years, shortest of the Great Lakes"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1830,text:"Shallowest, warmest, and most biologically productive of the Great Lakes, named for the Erie people destroyed in the 1600s Beaver Wars. Wyandot, Odawa, Seneca, and Lenape communities used its marshy shores, and the vast Black Swamp guarded its southwest corner. Perry's 1813 victory at Put-in-Bay decided control of the upper lakes in the War of 1812."},
  {from:1830,to:1900,text:"The Erie Canal's Buffalo terminus and later the railroads made the lake a freight corridor, and Cleveland and Toledo boomed on coal, iron, and oil. Settlers drained the Black Swamp into some of America's richest farmland, erasing vast wetlands, while walleye, herring, and blue pike supported the world's largest freshwater fishery."},
  {from:1900,to:1972,text:"Steel, refineries, and cities loaded the shallow lake with waste and phosphorus; by the 1960s algal mats and fish kills had headlines declaring Lake Erie dying, and the Cuyahoga River fire of 1969 became the era's emblem. The blue pike, once landed by the tens of millions, was fished and polluted into extinction."},
  {from:1972,to:2026,text:"The Clean Water Act and the US-Canada water quality agreement cut phosphorus sharply, and the lake rebounded into a walleye capital by the 1980s. Zebra mussels made their North American debut here in 1988. Dissolved farm runoff then revived toxic cyanobacteria blooms; the 2014 Toledo bloom cut drinking water to nearly half a million people."}
 ],
 sources:["NOAA","Encyclopaedia Britannica"]},
{id:"lakeontario",name:"Lake Ontario",kind:"lake",lon:-77.8,lat:43.6,angle:0,tier:2,
 facts:[["Area","7,340 square miles; smallest Great Lake by surface"],["Average depth","283 ft; holds about four times Lake Erie's volume"],["Outlet","Drains the entire Great Lakes system via the St. Lawrence"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1830,text:"Smallest of the Great Lakes in surface but deep, Ontario, from a Haudenosaunee word for a beautiful or great lake, was ringed by Seneca, Cayuga, Onondaga, and Mississauga homelands. French and British forts at Niagara, Oswego, and Frontenac contested its trade; the 1779 Sullivan campaign burned Haudenosaunee towns, and Loyalists settled the north shore."},
  {from:1830,to:1900,text:"The Erie Canal of 1825 and Welland Canal of 1829 wired the lake into continental commerce, and Oswego and Rochester milled grain with tributary water power. Dams and deforestation extinguished the lake's native Atlantic salmon by the late 1800s, one of North America's first great fishery losses."},
  {from:1900,to:1970,text:"Hydropower and chemical industry concentrated near the Niagara River inlet, leaving toxic legacies such as Love Canal. The 1959 St. Lawrence Seaway brought ocean ships upstream and cemented invasion routes the canals had opened: sea lamprey and alewife reshaped the fish community as native trout and ciscoes fell."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"Pacific salmon stocked since 1968 built a sport fishery atop the alewife, while Atlantic salmon restoration proceeds modestly. Cleanup shrank toxic hotspots on both shores. Plan 2014 water-level regulation, tested by record floods in 2017 and 2019, balances shorelines, shipping, and coastal wetlands, which benefit from more natural level swings."}
 ],
 sources:["NOAA","Encyclopaedia Britannica"]},
{id:"greatsaltlake",name:"Great Salt Lake",kind:"lake",lon:-112.5,lat:41.2,angle:0,tier:3,
 facts:[["Rank","Largest saltwater lake in the Western Hemisphere"],["Salinity","Up to about 27% in the cut-off north arm"],["Record low","About 4,188.5 ft elevation, November 2022"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1847,text:"The Great Basin's inland sea is the shrunken remnant of Ice Age Lake Bonneville, whose old shorelines terrace the surrounding mountains. Too salty for fish, it teems with brine shrimp and brine flies that feed millions of migrating birds. Shoshone, Goshute, and Ute peoples lived at its freshwater edges; trappers tasted its salt water in 1824-25."},
  {from:1847,to:1900,text:"Fremont mapped the lake in 1843, and Latter-day Saint settlers arriving in 1847 immediately began diverting its tributaries, the Bear, Weber, and Jordan, for irrigation. The transcontinental railroad met at Promontory north of the lake in 1869, and the Saltair resort of 1893 launched a shoreline bathing tradition."},
  {from:1900,to:1959,text:"Mineral industries worked the brines for salt, then potash and magnesium, and brine shrimp harvests later fed a global aquaculture trade. In 1959 a railroad rock-fill causeway split the lake in two; the northern arm, starved of river inflow, turned hypersaline and pink with salt-loving microbes."},
  {from:1959,to:2026,text:"Wet years drove a record high in 1986-87 that flooded shoreline works, and Utah pumped lake water into the desert; then diversion and drought reversed everything. In November 2022 the lake hit a record low near 4,188.5 feet, exposing hundreds of square miles of dusty, arsenic-bearing lakebed beside two million people; emergency laws and wet winters lifted it only modestly."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","Encyclopaedia Britannica"]},
{id:"chesapeake",name:"Chesapeake Bay",kind:"bay",lon:-76.2,lat:38.3,angle:0,tier:2,
 facts:[["Size","About 200 miles long; largest estuary in the US"],["Watershed","About 64,000 square miles across six states"],["Average depth","Only about 21 ft"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1800,text:"North America's largest estuary is the drowned valley of the Susquehanna, flooded by rising seas after the Ice Age, with a 35-million-year-old meteor impact crater buried beneath its mouth. Powhatan, Piscataway, Nanticoke, and Susquehannock peoples harvested oyster reefs that grew to the surface; by 1750 tobacco plantations worked by enslaved people lined its tidal rivers."},
  {from:1800,to:1900,text:"After the 1814 bombardment of Fort McHenry, the century belonged to the oyster: dredgers landed around twenty million bushels a year at the 1880s peak, policed by an Oyster Navy amid the armed Oyster Wars. Watermen's skipjacks became icons while forests and wetlands around the bay fell to farms."},
  {from:1900,to:1983,text:"Harvests slid as the reefs were mined away, and the diseases MSX and Dermo, spreading from the 1950s, pushed oysters toward one percent of historic abundance. Sewage, sediment, and farm nutrients clouded the water; underwater grasses crashed after Tropical Storm Agnes in 1972, and blue crabs became the bay's last great fishery."},
  {from:1983,to:2026,text:"The 1983 Chesapeake Bay Program launched the nation's flagship estuary restoration, and a 2010 pollution diet set enforceable nutrient caps. Underwater grasses rebounded to modern records, some of the world's largest oyster-reef restorations rose in Maryland and Virginia sanctuaries, and summer dead zones are slowly shrinking, though farm runoff and warming hold recovery back."}
 ],
 sources:["NOAA","U.S. Geological Survey"]},
{id:"mississippidelta",name:"Mississippi River Delta",kind:"delta",lon:-89.6,lat:29.3,angle:0,tier:3,
 facts:[["Age","Built by shifting river lobes over about 7,000 years"],["Land loss","Roughly 2,000 square miles of Louisiana lost since the 1930s"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1830,text:"Built over seven millennia as the river swung between sediment lobes, the delta's marshes, natural levees, and bayous form the largest wetland complex in the contiguous US. Chitimacha, Houma, and Atakapa peoples lived on its ridges and shell middens; French New Orleans, founded in 1718, rose on a natural levee, and Acadian exiles settled the bayous after 1755."},
  {from:1830,to:1930,text:"Sugar and cotton plantations worked by enslaved people walled the river with private levees, and Eads' jetties of 1879 secured deep-water commerce at the mouth. The 1927 flood shattered the levees-only doctrine; engineers dynamited a levee below New Orleans to spare the city, flooding rural parishes downstream."},
  {from:1930,to:2005,text:"Federal levees sealed the river off from its marshes, starving them of the sediment that built the land, while oil and gas development cut roughly 10,000 miles of canals that let salt water in. Louisiana has lost about 2,000 square miles of coastal land since the 1930s; introduced nutria stripped marsh roots, and low-lying communities began to drown."},
  {from:2005,to:2026,text:"Katrina's 2005 surge, amplified by wetland loss, killed more than 1,800 people and led to a roughly $14 billion defense ring around New Orleans; the 2010 Deepwater Horizon spill oiled marsh edges. State coastal master plans fund dredged marsh-building and river diversions, including the contested Mid-Barataria project begun in 2023, while relocation from the sinking fringe has started."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Army Corps of Engineers","U.S. Geological Survey","NOAA"]},
{id:"everglades",name:"The Everglades",kind:"wetland",lon:-80.9,lat:26.1,angle:0,tier:2,
 facts:[["Historic extent","About 3 million acres of wetland; roughly half remains"],["Everglades National Park","About 1.5 million acres"],["Gradient","Only about 2 inches of fall per mile"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1880,text:"A river of grass: a sheet of water inches deep and up to 60 miles wide creeping from Lake Okeechobee over limestone to Florida Bay, building peat for about 5,000 years. The Calusa and Tequesta domains had collapsed by 1750; during the Seminole Wars of 1817-58, Seminole and Miccosukee people withdrew deep into the wetland and never surrendered."},
  {from:1880,to:1947,text:"Drainage began with Disston's dredges in the 1880s and Governor Broward's canals after 1905, and the Tamiami Trail of 1928 dammed the sheet flow. Hurricanes in 1926 and 1928 drowned thousands at Okeechobee, bringing the Hoover Dike. Plume hunters had stripped wading-bird rookeries for the hat trade until wardens and new laws intervened."},
  {from:1947,to:2000,text:"Marjory Stoneman Douglas published The Everglades: River of Grass in 1947, the year the national park was dedicated. The Central and Southern Florida Project then re-plumbed the region with about 1,700 miles of canals and levees for cities and sugar; half the original Everglades vanished, wading birds fell about 90 percent, and a 1969 jetport plan was defeated."},
  {from:2000,to:2026,text:"The Comprehensive Everglades Restoration Plan of 2000, the largest ecosystem restoration ever attempted, slowly rebuilds southward flow: miles of the Tamiami Trail now stand on bridges and a vast reservoir is under construction. Invasive Burmese pythons have erased most small mammals in the park, and seagrass die-offs keep pressure on Florida Bay."}
 ],
 sources:["National Park Service","U.S. Geological Survey"]},
{id:"outerbanks",name:"Outer Banks",kind:"coast",lon:-75.6,lat:35.5,angle:0,tier:3,
 facts:[["Length","About 175 miles of barrier islands"],["Cape Hatteras Lighthouse","198 ft; tallest brick lighthouse in the US"],["Shipwrecks","More than 1,000 offshore; the Graveyard of the Atlantic"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1850,text:"A thin ribbon of barrier islands standing off North Carolina's sounds, post-glacial sand that survives by rolling landward through storm overwash. Croatoan and Roanoke Algonquian communities fished here when the 1580s Roanoke colonies came and vanished. By 1750 the banks held pilots, stockmen, and salvagers beside the shoals where warm and cold currents collide off Hatteras."},
  {from:1850,to:1937,text:"Lighthouses rose, including Cape Hatteras in 1870, at 198 feet the nation's tallest brick light, along with US Life-Saving stations such as Pea Island's all-Black crew. The Wright brothers flew at Kill Devil Hills in 1903. Storms opened and closed inlets while villagers lived by fishing, piloting, and salvage."},
  {from:1937,to:1990,text:"New Deal crews built an artificial dune line along the beaches, and Cape Hatteras became the first national seashore, authorized in 1937 and established in 1953. German U-boats sank dozens of ships offshore in 1942's Torpedo Junction. Postwar bridges and Highway 12 opened a tourism economy that remade the villages."},
  {from:1990,to:2026,text:"Erosion and rising seas now dominate: the Cape Hatteras lighthouse was moved 2,900 feet inland in 1999, Highway 12 breached repeatedly in hurricanes Isabel, Irene, and Dorian, and beach houses at Rodanthe collapsed into the surf in the 2020s, forcing buyouts and debate over retreat from the migrating islands."}
 ],
 sources:["National Park Service","NOAA"]},
{id:"niagara",name:"Niagara Falls",kind:"falls",lon:-79.07,lat:43.08,angle:0,tier:2,
 facts:[["Height","Horseshoe Falls, about 167 ft"],["Age","About 12,000 years; the falls have retreated roughly 7 miles"],["Flow split","About 90% of the river passes over Horseshoe Falls"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1885,text:"Born about 12,000 years ago when glacial meltwater sent the Great Lakes' outlet over the Niagara Escarpment, the falls have since retreated seven miles upstream. The name descends from Onguiaahra; Haudenosaunee and earlier Neutral peoples controlled the vital portage that French and British forts contested. By the mid-1800s mills crowded the brink, honeymoon tourism boomed, and Blondin crossed on a tightrope in 1859."},
  {from:1885,to:1950,text:"New York's Niagara Reservation of 1885, landscaped by Olmsted, became the nation's oldest state park and freed the falls from private fee-takers. The 1895 Adams plant sent Tesla-Westinghouse alternating current to Buffalo in 1896, proving long-distance power transmission and drawing electrochemical industry; Annie Taylor survived the first barrel plunge in 1901."},
  {from:1950,to:1970,text:"A 1950 US-Canada treaty guaranteed minimum flows over the falls for spectacle while diverting much of the river through power tunnels. After a 1956 rockslide wrecked the Schoellkopf station, the Robert Moses plant of 1961 became one of the largest hydro stations in the West; in 1969 engineers shut off the American Falls entirely to study its rock face."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"Diversion and engineering slowed the falls' retreat from several feet a year to a few inches. The 1978 Love Canal emergency just downstream became a national benchmark of toxic legacy and cleanup. Millions visit each year, hydropower remains a mainstay of the region, and Nik Wallenda's permitted 2012 wire walk revived the daredevil tradition."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","Encyclopaedia Britannica"]},
{id:"pugetsound",name:"Puget Sound",kind:"sound",lon:-122.6,lat:47.8,angle:0,tier:3,
 facts:[["Depth","Up to about 930 ft"],["Origin","Carved by the Vashon glacial lobe roughly 16,000 years ago"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1850,text:"A branching fjord system carved by the Vashon ice lobe about 16,000 years ago, more than 900 feet deep in places. Coast Salish peoples, among them the Duwamish, Suquamish, Nisqually, and Puyallup, thrived on salmon, shellfish, and cedar in one of the continent's most populous Indigenous regions. Vancouver charted and named the sound in 1792; Fort Nisqually followed in 1833."},
  {from:1850,to:1900,text:"The 1854-55 treaties of Medicine Creek and Point Elliott ceded vast lands while reserving fishing at usual and accustomed grounds, a promise that would define the next century and a half. Sawmills at Port Gamble and Seattle shipped old-growth timber worldwide, and the Mosquito Fleet of small steamers stitched the shoreline towns together."},
  {from:1900,to:1974,text:"Naval shipyards at Bremerton, Boeing's plants, and Tacoma's smelter industrialized the shores, and the Duwamish estuary was straightened into an industrial waterway later declared a Superfund site. State ferries replaced the steamers, pollution and dams cut salmon runs, and officers arrested tribal fishers during the fish wars of the 1960s and 1970s."},
  {from:1974,to:2026,text:"Judge Boldt's 1974 ruling affirmed treaty tribes' right to half the harvestable salmon and made them co-managers. Chinook were federally listed in 1999 and the Southern Resident orcas, now only about 75 animals, in 2005. Superfund cleanups, the Nisqually delta restoration of 2009, and a 2018 culvert ruling push recovery against continuing shoreline growth."}
 ],
 sources:["NOAA","U.S. Geological Survey"]},
{id:"hawaiianislands",name:"Hawaiian Islands",kind:"islands",lon:-156.6,lat:20.6,angle:0,tier:2,
 facts:[["Highest point","Mauna Kea, 13,796 ft; about 33,000 ft from seafloor to summit"],["Origin","Hotspot volcanism; islands age toward the northwest"],["Kilauea","Among the most active volcanoes on Earth"]],
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1810,text:"Conveyor-belt volcanism built the chain as the Pacific plate slides over a stationary hotspot: Kauai is about five million years old while Hawai'i Island still grows, and Mauna Kea stands taller from seafloor to summit than Everest above the sea. Polynesian navigators had settled the islands around a thousand years ago, organizing land in ahupua'a divisions with fishponds and taro terraces. Cook arrived in 1778, and introduced diseases began a catastrophic population decline."},
  {from:1810,to:1898,text:"Kamehameha I unified the kingdom by 1810. Sandalwood cutting stripped forests, whaling fleets crowded Lahaina and Honolulu, and missionaries arrived in 1820. The 1848 Mahele privatized land, easing plantation acquisition, and sugar growers imported labor from Asia and Portugal. In 1893 American businessmen backed by US Marines overthrew Queen Lili'uokalani; annexation followed in 1898."},
  {from:1898,to:1959,text:"Territorial Hawai'i ran on sugar and pineapple plantations dominated by a handful of firms. Pearl Harbor became the Pacific fleet's base and the target of the December 1941 attack that brought the US into World War II, followed by years of martial law. Cattle ranching and introduced species kept eroding native forests and endemic birds."},
  {from:1959,to:2026,text:"Statehood in 1959 and jet travel built a tourism economy approaching ten million annual visitors. The 1976 Hokule'a voyage powered a Hawaiian cultural renaissance, and a 1993 congressional resolution apologized for the overthrow. The islands remain a global center of species endangerment; Kilauea's 2018 eruption destroyed about 700 homes, and the 2023 Lahaina fire killed 102 people."}
 ],
 sources:["U.S. Geological Survey","National Park Service"]}
];
